# Velocity Takeoff Engine — Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
This is an AI-powered HVAC Bill of Materials takeoff system for Velocity Sheet Metal.
It processes mechanical plan PDFs to extract ductwork, air devices, equipment, and
fittings into itemized BOMs for bid generation.

## Tech Stack
- Next.js 15 with App Router (TypeScript)
- Vercel AI SDK for multi-agent AI pipeline
- Supabase (PostgreSQL + Auth + Storage + Realtime)
- Tailwind CSS for styling

## Architecture
- 7 specialized AI agents in src/agents/
- Agents use different models: Claude Opus, Claude Sonnet, GPT-4o, Gemini Pro
- Agent 3 (Component Spotter) runs TWO models in parallel for accuracy
- Agent 6 (Reconciliation) merges outputs and assigns confidence scores
- All agents use Vercel AI SDK's generateObject() with Zod schemas

## Conventions
- Use Vercel AI SDK patterns (generateObject, generateText, streamText)
- All agent outputs must conform to Zod schemas
- API routes go in src/app/api/
- Use Supabase JS client for all database operations
- Store files in Supabase Storage (S3-compatible)
- Pricing: rectangular duct by weight (lbs), round duct by linear foot

## Key Models
- anthropic('claude-opus-4-6') — component extraction, measurement, reconciliation
- anthropic('claude-sonnet-4-6') — classification, validation
- openai('gpt-4o') — parallel component extraction
- google('gemini-2.0-pro') — schedule reading, QA audit

## Important
- All duct measurements use user-provided drawing scale (not AI-detected)
- Scale is stored per-project with optional per-sheet overrides
- Confidence scoring: HIGH (both models agree), MEDIUM (minor discrepancy), LOW (one model only)